[0m[49m[39m  158, 163[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  159, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  160, 165[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  161, 166[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  162, 167[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Step Functions, Amazon QuickSight |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 163     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions (orchestration)** | `sagemaker:CreateProcessingJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions (SageMaker execution role)** | `s3:GetObject` on `features/*`, `s3:PutObject` on `optimization-results/*` and `simulation-results/*`. This role should not have DynamoDB or Step Functions access. |
[0m[49m[39m  164, 170[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (scheduling data contains patient names and visit reasons, which are PHI) |
[0m[49m[39m  165, 171[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; SageMaker: VPC mode with encrypted volumes |
[0m[49m[39m  166, 172[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | SageMaker Processing jobs in VPC with no internet access; VPC endpoints for S3 (gateway), DynamoDB (gateway), CloudWatch Logs (interface), and STS (interface). If using custom container images, add ECR endpoints (dkr and api). Security groups should allow outbound HTTPS (443) to VPC endpoint prefix lists. |
[0m[49m[39m  167, 173[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for all API calls; audit trail for template changes |
[0m[49m[39m  168, 174[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic scheduling data. Use realistic visit type distributions but never real patient identifiers in dev. |
[0m[49m[39m  169, 175[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker Processing: ~$2-5 per optimization run (ml.m5.xlarge, 10-30 min). S3 + DynamoDB + Lambda: negligible. Monthly total for weekly runs: $50-200. |
[0m[49m[39m  170, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  171, 177[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  172, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  173, 179[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  174, 180[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  175, 181[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Runs optimization solver and simulation validation as Processing jobs |
[0m[49m[39m  176, 182[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores historical data, features, optimization results, simulation outputs |
[0m[49m[39m  177, 183[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates data extraction, feature computation, and EHR template push |
[0m[49m[39m  178, 184[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores template versions with state management (proposed/approved/active) |
[0m[49m[39m  179, 185[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Coordinates the multi-step pipeline with error handling and retries |
[0m[49m[39m  180, 186[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Visualization layer for human review of proposed templates |
[0m[49m[39m  181, 187[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data at rest |
[0m[49m[39m  182, 188[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  183, 189[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  184, 190[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  185, 191[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  186, 192[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  187, 193[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract and prepare historical data.** The pipeline begins by pulling scheduling data from your EHR system. You need actual visit durations (not scheduled durations), visit type codes, provider IDs, appointment times, check-in times, and show/no-show status. Most EHRs expose this through reporting databases or bulk export APIs. The extraction runs nightly or weekly, appending new data to the historical store. Without accurate historical durations, the entire optimization is garbage-in-garbage-out. Scheduled duration tells you what the template says; actual duration tells you what really happens.
[0m[49m[39m  188, 194[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 189     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  190, 196[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_scheduling_data(start_date, end_date):
[0m[49m[39m  191, 197[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull completed appointments from the EHR reporting database.
[0m[49m[39m  192, 198[0m:[39m[49m     // We need ACTUAL durations, not scheduled durations.
[0m[49m[39m  193, 199[0m:[39m[49m     // "Actual" means check-in to checkout, or room-in to room-out depending on your system.
[0m[49m[39m  194, 200[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  195, 201[0m:[39m[49m     raw_data = query EHR database:
[0m[49m[39m  196, 202[0m:[39m[49m         SELECT appointment_id, provider_id, visit_type, scheduled_time,
[0m[49m[39m  197, 203[0m:[39m[49m                checkin_time, checkout_time, no_show_flag, cancellation_flag
[0m[49m[39m  198, 204[0m:[39m[49m         WHERE appointment_date BETWEEN start_date AND end_date
[0m[49m[39m  199, 205[0m:[39m[49m         AND status IN ('completed', 'no_show', 'cancelled')
[0m[49m[39m  200, 206[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  201, 207[0m:[39m[49m     // Calculate actual duration for completed visits
[0m[49m[39m  202, 208[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each record in raw_data:
[0m[49m[39m  203, 209[0m:[39m[49m         IF record.no_show_flag == false AND record.cancellation_flag == false:
[0m[49m[39m  204, 210[0m:[39m[49m             record.actual_duration = minutes_between(record.checkin_time, record.checkout_time)
[0m[49m[39m  205, 211[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  206, 212[0m:[39m[49m             record.actual_duration = 0  // no-shows and cancellations consumed zero clinical time
[0m[49m[39m  207, 213[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  208, 214[0m:[39m[49m     // Store in S3, partitioned by provider and month for efficient downstream queries
[0m[49m[39m  209, 215[0m:[39m[49m     write raw_data to S3 at "raw-scheduling-data/{provider_id}/{year}/{month}/"
[0m[49m[39m  210, 216[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  211, 217[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN record count written
[0m[49m[39m  212, 218[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  213, 219[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  214, 220[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Compute statistical features.** This step transforms raw appointment records into the statistics the optimizer needs. For each provider and visit type combination, compute the mean and standard deviation of actual visit duration, the no-show rate by hour-of-day, and the late arrival distribution. The standard deviation is arguably more important than the mean: a visit type with high variance creates cascading delays that ripple through the entire afternoon. Skip this step and your optimizer will assume every 20-minute visit takes exactly 20 minutes, which is a fantasy.
[0m[49m[39m  215, 221[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 216     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  217, 223[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION compute_features(provider_id):
[0m[49m[39m  218, 224[0m:[39m[49m     // Load historical data for this provider (at least 6 months for seasonal stability)
[0m[49m[39m  219, 225[0m:[39m[49m     historical = load from S3 "raw-scheduling-data/{provider_id}/*"
[0m[49m[39m  220, 226[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  221, 227[0m:[39m[49m     features = empty structure
[0m[49m[39m  222, 228[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  223, 229[0m:[39m[49m     // Duration statistics by visit type
[0m[49m[39m  224, 230[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each visit_type in unique(historical.visit_type):
[0m[49m[39m  225, 231[0m:[39m[49m         type_records = filter historical where visit_type matches AND actual_duration > 0
[0m[49m[39m  226, 232[0m:[39m[49m         features.duration_stats[visit_type] = {
[0m[49m[39m  227, 233[0m:[39m[49m             mean:   average(type_records.actual_duration),
[0m[49m[39m  228, 234[0m:[39m[49m             stddev: standard_deviation(type_records.actual_duration),
[0m[49m[39m  229, 235[0m:[39m[49m             p90:    percentile(type_records.actual_duration, 90),  // 90th percentile for buffer planning
[0m[49m[39m  230, 236[0m:[39m[49m             count:  length(type_records)  // sample size for confidence
[0m[49m[39m  231, 237[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  232, 238[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  233, 239[0m:[39m[49m     // No-show rates by hour block
[0m[49m[39m  234, 240[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each hour_block in [8, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16]:
[0m[49m[39m  235, 241[0m:[39m[49m         block_records = filter historical where hour(scheduled_time) == hour_block
[0m[49m[39m  236, 242[0m:[39m[49m         features.noshow_rate[hour_block] = count(no_show_flag == true) / count(block_records)
[0m[49m[39m  237, 243[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  238, 244[0m:[39m[49m     // Late arrival distribution (minutes past scheduled time)
[0m[49m[39m  239, 245[0m:[39m[49m     arrived = filter historical where checkin_time is not null
[0m[49m[39m  240, 246[0m:[39m[49m     features.late_arrival = {
[0m[49m[39m  241, 247[0m:[39m[49m         mean:   average(minutes_between(scheduled_time, checkin_time)),
[0m[49m[39m  242, 248[0m:[39m[49m         stddev: standard_deviation(minutes_between(scheduled_time, checkin_time))
[0m[49m[39m  243, 249[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  244, 250[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  245, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // Store computed features
[0m[49m[39m  246, 252[0m:[39m[49m     write features to S3 at "features/{provider_id}/latest.json"
[0m[49m[39m  247, 253[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  248, 254[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[39m  249, 255[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  250, 256[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  251, 257[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Run the optimization solver.** This is the core of the recipe. Given the statistical features and organizational constraints, find the template configuration that maximizes throughput while keeping wait times acceptable. The solver explores the space of possible slot durations, buffer times, and overbooking levels to find the combination that best satisfies the objective function. For a typical clinic with 5-8 visit types and a single provider session, this solves in under a minute on modest hardware. The output is a proposed template: a sequence of slot types with durations and any overbooking recommendations.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 258[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 253     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  254, 260[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION optimize_template(features, constraints):
[0m[49m[39m  255, 261[0m:[39m[49m     // constraints includes: session_start, session_end, break_time, break_duration,
[0m[49m[39m  256, 262[0m:[39m[49m     //                       max_wait_minutes, max_overbook_per_hour, visit_type_mix
[0m[49m[39m  257, 263[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  258, 264[0m:[39m[49m     // Define decision variables
[0m[49m[39m  259, 265[0m:[39m[49m     // d[t] = slot duration for visit type t (continuous, in minutes)
[0m[49m[39m  260, 266[0m:[39m[49m     // o[h] = overbooking count for hour h (integer, 0 to max_overbook)
[0m[49m[39m  261, 267[0m:[39m[49m     // b    = buffer time between slots (continuous, in minutes)
[0m[49m[39m  262, 268[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  263, 269[0m:[39m[49m     model = create optimization model
[0m[49m[39m  264, 270[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  265, 271[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each visit_type t:
[0m[49m[39m  266, 272[0m:[39m[49m         // Slot duration must be between clinical minimum and maximum
[0m[49m[39m  267, 273[0m:[39m[49m         add variable d[t] with bounds:
[0m[49m[39m  268, 274[0m:[39m[49m             lower = constraints.clinical_minimum[t]   // e.g., 10 min for BP recheck
[0m[49m[39m  269, 275[0m:[39m[49m             upper = constraints.clinical_maximum[t]   // e.g., 60 min for new patient
[0m[49m[39m  270, 276[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  271, 277[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each hour_block h:
[0m[49m[39m  272, 278[0m:[39m[49m         add integer variable o[h] with bounds:
[0m[49m[39m  273, 279[0m:[39m[49m             lower = 0
[0m[49m[39m  274, 280[0m:[39m[49m             upper = constraints.max_overbook_per_hour  // e.g., 2
[0m[49m[39m  275, 281[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  276, 282[0m:[39m[49m     add variable b (buffer) with bounds:
[0m[49m[39m  277, 283[0m:[39m[49m         lower = 0
[0m[49m[39m  278, 284[0m:[39m[49m         upper = 15  // no more than 15 minutes buffer between any two slots
[0m[49m[39m  279, 285[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  280, 286[0m:[39m[49m     // Objective: maximize expected patients seen, penalized by expected wait
[0m[49m[39m  281, 287[0m:[39m[49m     // Expected patients = scheduled patients * (1 - noshow_rate) + overbooked * (1 - noshow_rate)
[0m[49m[39m  282, 288[0m:[39m[49m     // Expected wait is approximated using queuing theory (M/G/1 queue approximation)
[0m[49m[39m  283, 289[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  284, 290[0m:[39m[49m     expected_throughput = SUM over hour_blocks h:
[0m[49m[39m  285, 291[0m:[39m[49m         (base_slots_per_hour[h] + o[h]) * (1 - features.noshow_rate[h])
[0m[49m[39m  286, 292[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  287, 293[0m:[39m[49m     // Pollaczek-Khinchine formula approximation for expected wait
[0m[49m[39m  288, 294[0m:[39m[49m     // W = (rho * (cv^2 + 1)) / (2 * (1 - rho) * mu)
[0m[49m[39m  289, 295[0m:[39m[49m     // where rho = utilization, cv = coefficient of variation of service time
[0m[49m[39m  290, 296[0m:[39m[49m     expected_wait = compute_expected_wait(features.duration_stats, d, b)
[0m[49m[39m  291, 297[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  292, 298[0m:[39m[49m     // Combined objective with tradeoff parameter lambda
[0m[49m[39m  293, 299[0m:[39m[49m     lambda = constraints.wait_penalty  // tunable: higher = more wait-averse
[0m[49m[39m  294, 300[0m:[39m[49m     set objective: MAXIMIZE expected_throughput - lambda * expected_wait
[0m[49m[39m  295, 301[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  296, 302[0m:[39m[49m     // Constraints
[0m[49m[39m  297, 303[0m:[39m[49m     // Total scheduled time must fit in session
[0m[49m[39m  298, 304[0m:[39m[49m     session_minutes = minutes_between(constraints.session_start, constraints.session_end)
[0m[49m[39m  299, 305[0m:[39m[49m                       - constraints.break_duration
[0m[49m[39m  300, 306[0m:[39m[49m     add constraint: SUM(slots * (d[type_of_slot] + b)) <= session_minutes
[0m[49m[39m  301, 307[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  302, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // Solve
[0m[49m[39m  303, 309[0m:[39m[49m     solution = solve model with time_limit = 300 seconds
[0m[49m[39m  304, 310[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  305, 311[0m:[39m[49m     // Extract proposed template
[0m[49m[39m  306, 312[0m:[39m[49m     proposed_template = {
[0m[49m[39m  307, 313[0m:[39m[49m         slot_durations: { t: value(d[t]) for each visit_type t },
[0m[49m[39m  308, 314[0m:[39m[49m         buffer_minutes: value(b),
[0m[49m[39m  309, 315[0m:[39m[49m         overbooking:    { h: value(o[h]) for each hour_block h },
[0m[49m[39m  310, 316[0m:[39m[49m         expected_throughput: value(expected_throughput),
[0m[49m[39m  311, 317[0m:[39m[49m         expected_avg_wait:   value(expected_wait)
[0m[49m[39m  312, 318[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  313, 319[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  314, 320[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN proposed_template
[0m[49m[39m  315, 321[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  316, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  317, 323[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Validate with simulation.** The optimization model makes simplifying assumptions (steady-state queuing, independent arrivals). Simulation tests the proposed template against messy reality. Run 1,000+ replications of a clinic day using the proposed template, drawing visit durations from the historical distribution, simulating no-shows probabilistically, and tracking actual wait times and overtime. Compare against the same simulation using the current template. If the proposed template doesn't beat the current one by a meaningful margin (say, 5% improvement in throughput or 10% reduction in wait time), don't recommend the change. Template changes have operational cost.
[0m[49m[39m  318, 324[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 319     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  320, 326[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION simulate_clinic_day(template, features, num_replications):
[0m[49m[39m  321, 327[0m:[39m[49m     // Note: this simulation assumes provider behavior doesn't change under the new
[0m[49m[39m  322, 328[0m:[39m[49m     // template. In practice, providers may adjust their pace in response to shorter
[0m[49m[39m  323, 329[0m:[39m[49m     // or longer slots. Treat results as directional estimates, not guarantees.
[0m[49m[39m  324, 330[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  325, 331[0m:[39m[49m     results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  326, 332[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  327, 333[0m:[39m[49m     FOR rep = 1 to num_replications:
[0m[49m[39m  328, 334[0m:[39m[49m         // Generate a random clinic day using historical distributions
[0m[49m[39m  329, 335[0m:[39m[49m         schedule = generate_schedule_from_template(template)
[0m[49m[39m  330, 336[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  331, 337[0m:[39m[49m         current_time = template.session_start
[0m[49m[39m  332, 338[0m:[39m[49m         wait_times = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  333, 339[0m:[39m[49m         patients_seen = 0
[0m[49m[39m  334, 340[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  335, 341[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each slot in schedule:
[0m[49m[39m  336, 342[0m:[39m[49m             // Determine if patient shows up (Bernoulli draw based on no-show rate)
[0m[49m[39m  337, 343[0m:[39m[49m             shows_up = random() > features.noshow_rate[hour_of(slot.time)]
[0m[49m[39m  338, 344[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  339, 345[0m:[39m[49m             IF shows_up:
[0m[49m[39m  340, 346[0m:[39m[49m                 // Draw actual visit duration from historical distribution for this type
[0m[49m[39m  341, 347[0m:[39m[49m                 actual_duration = draw_from_distribution(
[0m[49m[39m  342, 348[0m:[39m[49m                     mean = features.duration_stats[slot.visit_type].mean,
[0m[49m[39m  343, 349[0m:[39m[49m                     stddev = features.duration_stats[slot.visit_type].stddev
[0m[49m[39m  344, 350[0m:[39m[49m                 )
[0m[49m[39m  345, 351[0m:[39m[49m                 
[0m[49m[39m  346, 352[0m:[39m[49m                 // Patient wait = max(0, current_time - slot.scheduled_time)
[0m[49m[39m  347, 353[0m:[39m[49m                 patient_wait = max(0, current_time - slot.scheduled_time)
[0m[49m[39m  348, 354[0m:[39m[49m                 append patient_wait to wait_times
[0m[49m[39m  349, 355[0m:[39m[49m                 
[0m[49m[39m  350, 356[0m:[39m[49m                 // Provider finishes at current_time + actual_duration + buffer
[0m[49m[39m  351, 357[0m:[39m[49m                 current_time = max(current_time, slot.scheduled_time) + actual_duration + template.buffer
[0m[49m[39m  352, 358[0m:[39m[49m                 patients_seen = patients_seen + 1
[0m[49m[39m  353, 359[0m:[39m[49m             ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  354, 360[0m:[39m[49m                 // No-show: time advances to next slot without clinical work
[0m[49m[39m  355, 361[0m:[39m[49m                 current_time = max(current_time, slot.scheduled_time + template.buffer)
[0m[49m[39m  356, 362[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  357, 363[0m:[39m[49m         // Record this replication's outcomes
[0m[49m[39m  358, 364[0m:[39m[49m         append to results: {
[0m[49m[39m  359, 365[0m:[39m[49m             patients_seen:    patients_seen,
[0m[49m[39m  360, 366[0m:[39m[49m             avg_wait:         average(wait_times),
[0m[49m[39m  361, 367[0m:[39m[49m             max_wait:         max(wait_times),
[0m[49m[39m  362, 368[0m:[39m[49m             overtime_minutes: max(0, current_time - template.session_end),
[0m[49m[39m  363, 369[0m:[39m[49m             provider_idle:    compute_idle_time(schedule, current_time)
[0m[49m[39m  364, 370[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  365, 371[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  366, 372[0m:[39m[49m     // Aggregate across replications
[0m[49m[39m  367, 373[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  368, 374[0m:[39m[49m         mean_throughput:  average(results.patients_seen),
[0m[49m[39m  369, 375[0m:[39m[49m         mean_wait:        average(results.avg_wait),
[0m[49m[39m  370, 376[0m:[39m[49m         p95_wait:         percentile(results.avg_wait, 95),
[0m[49m[39m  371, 377[0m:[39m[49m         overtime_prob:    count(results.overtime_minutes > 0) / num_replications,
[0m[49m[39m  372, 378[0m:[39m[49m         mean_idle:        average(results.provider_idle)
[0m[49m[39m  373, 379[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  374, 380[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  375, 381[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  376, 382[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Store and present for review.** Write the proposed template and simulation comparison to DynamoDB with a "proposed" status. Trigger a notification to the operations team. The review dashboard shows the current template performance alongside the proposed template performance, with explicit tradeoff visualization. Only after human approval does the template move to "active" status and get pushed to the EHR.
[0m[49m[39m  377, 383[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 378     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  379, 385[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_and_notify(provider_id, proposed_template, simulation_current, simulation_proposed):
[0m[49m[39m  380, 386[0m:[39m[49m     // Store the proposed template with full context for the reviewer
[0m[49m[39m  381, 387[0m:[39m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "template-store":
[0m[49m[39m  382, 388[0m:[39m[49m         provider_id      = provider_id
[0m[49m[39m  383, 389[0m:[39m[49m         version          = next_version_number(provider_id)
[0m[49m[39m  384, 390[0m:[39m[49m         status           = "proposed"                        // not active until approved
[0m[49m[39m  385, 391[0m:[39m[49m         created_at       = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  386, 392[0m:[39m[49m         approved_by      = null                              // populated on approval
[0m[49m[39m  387, 393[0m:[39m[49m         approved_at      = null                              // populated on approval
[0m[49m[39m  388, 394[0m:[39m[49m         approval_notes   = null                              // reviewer rationale
[0m[49m[39m  389, 395[0m:[39m[49m         template         = proposed_template                 // the actual slot configuration
[0m[49m[39m  390, 396[0m:[39m[49m         simulation_current  = simulation_current            // how today's template performs
[0m[49m[39m  391, 397[0m:[39m[49m         simulation_proposed = simulation_proposed           // how the new one performs
[0m[49m[39m  392, 398[0m:[39m[49m         improvement      = {
[0m[49m[39m  393, 399[0m:[39m[49m             throughput_delta: simulation_proposed.mean_throughput - simulation_current.mean_throughput,
[0m[49m[39m  394, 400[0m:[39m[49m             wait_delta:      simulation_proposed.mean_wait - simulation_current.mean_wait,
[0m[49m[39m  395, 401[0m:[39m[49m             overtime_delta:  simulation_proposed.overtime_prob - simulation_current.overtime_prob
[0m[49m[39m  396, 402[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  397, 403[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  398, 404[0m:[39m[49m     // Notify operations team that a new template is ready for review.
[0m[49m[39m  399, 405[0m:[39m[49m     // IMPORTANT: Do not embed provider-specific metrics in the notification body.
[0m[49m[39m  400, 406[0m:[39m[49m     // Notifications traverse channels that may not be encrypted end-to-end.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 407[0m:[39m[49m     // Send only a link to the authenticated review dashboard.
[0m[49m[39m  402, 408[0m:[39m[49m     send notification:
[0m[49m[39m  403, 409[0m:[39m[49m         to = operations_team_endpoint   // HTTPS endpoint or internal channel, not email
[0m[49m[39m  404, 410[0m:[39m[49m         subject = "New scheduling template ready for review"
[0m[49m[39m  405, 411[0m:[39m[49m         body = "A new template proposal is available. Review in the dashboard: {dashboard_url}"
[0m[49m[39m  406, 412[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  407, 413[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN version
[0m[49m[39m  408, 414[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  409, 415[0m:[39m[49m 
